Sure, here is a simple example of a webpage with HTML, CSS, and JS where you can click a button with different effects:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Button Effects</title>
<style>
button {
  width: 100px;
  height: 50px;
  background-color: blue;
  color: white;
  font-size: 24px;
  cursor: pointer;
}

button:hover {
  background-color: green;
}

button:active {
  background-color: red;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<button>Click Me</button>
<script>
var button = document.querySelector('button');
button.addEventListener('click', function() {
  this.style.backgroundColor = (this.style.backgroundColor === 'blue' ? 'green' : 'blue');
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code will create a button that changes color when you click it. You can change the colors and other properties of the button to create different effects.
